8-2 Journal: Portfolio Submission
The DriverPass project involved designing a cloud-based system for a new driver education company. 
DriverPass wanted a system that would help customers prepare for their DMV written and driving tests by offering online practice exams, educational content, and behind-the-wheel driving lessons. 
The system also needed to allow customers to register for training packages, schedule driving lessons, track their progress, and provide employees with tools to manage appointments, instructors, vehicles, reports, and user accounts. 
Throughout the course, I designed the business requirements, use case diagram, activity diagrams, sequence diagram, class diagram, and other system documentation needed to support the project. 
These requirements came directly from the DriverPass interview and guided each stage of the system design. 
I believe one of the strongest parts of my work was identifying the functional and nonfunctional requirements for the system. 
I made sure each requirement could be traced back to something the client requested during the interview, including role-based security, online scheduling, cloud access, password management, activity tracking, DMV updates, and reporting. 
I also think my UML diagrams clearly represented the relationships between users and the different functions of the DriverPass system, making it easier to understand how the system should operate. 
If I could revise one part of my work, I would spend more time improving the UML diagrams by adding additional details and refining the layout. As I learned more about system analysis throughout the course, I became more comfortable with UML notation and realized there were opportunities to make the diagrams easier to read while adding more business rules and decision points. 
Although my diagrams met the project requirements, I believe they could be improved by making them even more detailed and easier for stakeholders to follow.
Understanding the user's needs was the most important part of designing the DriverPass system. 
I carefully reviewed the interview transcript to identify what each type of user needed to accomplish. 
Customers needed to purchase training packages, schedule driving lessons, complete online practice exams, and monitor their progress. 
Employees needed different levels of access depending on their responsibilities, while management required reporting features and the IT officer needed administrative control over user accounts. 
Designing the system around these needs helped ensure the final design supported DriverPass's business goals while remaining easy for customers and employees to use. Considering the user's needs is essential because a technically correct system will still fail if it does not solve the client's real business problems. 
This course also changed how I approach software design. 
Instead of immediately thinking about programming, I now focus on understanding the business problem before designing the solution. 
I have learned that gathering complete requirements, creating process and object models, and using UML diagrams help identify problems early and improve communication between developers, stakeholders, and clients. 
In future projects, I plan to continue using interviews, requirement analysis, UML diagrams, and iterative design reviews to ensure that systems meet both technical requirements and user expectations.
